========================================================================
REPRESENTATION THEORY: WHY SYMMETRY CONSTRAINS H
========================================================================


  The orientation space of a circulant tournament on Z_p is {±1}^m
  where m = (p-1)/2 and sigma_j = +1 if j is in S, -1 otherwise.

  H(sigma) is a function on this Boolean cube.

  GROUP ACTION: If the tournament has automorphism group G, then
  G acts on {±1}^m by permuting coordinates. H must be G-INVARIANT.

  WALSH-FOURIER: H = sum_S hat{H}(S) chi_S(sigma)
  G-invariance means: hat{H}(S) = hat{H}(g.S) for all g in G.

  This FORCES Walsh coefficients to be EQUAL on each G-orbit.
  The number of INDEPENDENT Walsh coefficients = number of G-orbits on subsets.

  PALEY: G contains QR-multiplication (m elements).
    - At degree 2: Walsh pairs {i,j} are orbited by (i,j) -> (ai, aj) for a in QR
    - MANY pairs are in the same orbit => few independent degree-2 coefficients
    - At degree 4: even more collapsing

  INTERVAL: G is trivial on coordinates (only translation, which doesn't permute S).
    - ALL Walsh coefficients can be independent
    - MORE degrees of freedom to optimize H

  ANALOGY: Paley is like a crystal (high symmetry, rigid),
           Interval is like a glass (low symmetry, flexible).
           H-maximization at large p rewards FLEXIBILITY over RIGIDITY.

========================================================================
DIHEDRAL GROUP D_p AND THE EIGENVALUE STRUCTURE
========================================================================


  D_p = <r, s | r^p = s^2 = 1, srs = r^{-1}> has order 2p.

  For p odd prime, irreducible representations of D_p:
  - Two 1-dimensional: trivial and sign
  - (p-1)/2 two-dimensional: rho_j for j = 1, ..., (p-1)/2

  The adjacency matrix A of a circulant tournament on Z_p decomposes:
  A = sum_j mu_j * P_j where P_j are projections onto D_p irreps.

  KEY: The eigenvalues mu_j correspond to D_p representations!
  - mu_j and mu_{p-j} form a CONJUGATE PAIR (same 2D irrep rho_j)
  - This is why eigenvalues come in conjugate pairs

  For Paley: the EXTRA QR symmetry forces |mu_j| = |mu_k| for all j,k.
  This is because QR permutes the irreps transitively.
  Result: FLAT spectrum, all |mu_j| = sqrt(p)/2.

  For Interval: NO such constraint. |mu_1| can be much larger.
  Result: PEAKED spectrum, |mu_1| ~ p/pi >> sqrt(p)/2.

  THE DIHEDRAL PERSPECTIVE ON THE PHASE TRANSITION:

  At small p: there are few D_p irreps ((p-1)/2 of them).
    - The QR symmetry constraint (flat spectrum) is mild.
    - Paley's eigenvector advantage (THM-137) dominates.

  At large p: there are many D_p irreps.
    - The QR constraint WASTES most of the spectral budget.
    - Parseval forces sum |mu_j|^2 = p*m, but QR spreads this evenly.
    - Interval CONCENTRATES the budget, getting more from less.
    - Like the uncertainty principle: QR is spread in frequency (low |mu_1|),
      Interval is localized in frequency (high |mu_1|).

