========================================================================
SYNTHESIS: GROUP THEORY → PHASE TRANSITION → H-MAXIMIZATION
========================================================================


  THE COMPLETE PICTURE (via dihedral/group theory):

  1. STRUCTURE: Every circulant tournament on Z_p has connection set S ⊂ Z_p^*.
     The multiplicative stabilizer Stab(S) ≤ Z_p^* determines its symmetry.

  2. SPECTRUM: |Stab(S)| = k forces eigenvalue magnitudes to cluster into
     at most m/k distinct values. (Burnside on frequency domain.)
     - Paley: k = m, so ONE distinct |μ| value (flat spectrum)
     - Interval: k = 1, so m distinct |μ| values (can be peaked)

  3. WALSH FREEDOM: The number of independent even-degree Walsh coefficients
     of H is bounded by the number of Stab(S)-orbits on even-subsets.
     More freedom → larger achievable range for H.

  4. PHASE TRANSITION: At small p, degree-2 Walsh dominates. Paley MAXIMIZES
     degree-2 (THM-137: σ_P is eigenvector of J). So Paley wins.
     At large p, degree-4+ Walsh dominates. Interval has ~m times more
     degree-4 freedom, allowing it to achieve higher H. So Interval wins.

  5. THE DIHEDRAL GROUP D_p provides the natural framework:
     - Rotation = Z_p translation (all circulants are invariant)
     - Reflection = taking opposite tournament (H is invariant)
     - The nontrivial content is in the INTERNAL symmetry (Stab(S))
     - Paley's Stab = QR ≅ Z_m is the unique index-2 subgroup
     - This is MAXIMAL symmetry, which is SUBOPTIMAL for H at large p

  6. PREDICTION: The H-maximizing circulant tournament at large p has:
     - Connection set with |Stab| = 1 (minimal symmetry)
     - Eigenvalue distribution concentrated at |μ_1| (anti-Ramanujan)
     - S = {1,...,m} is a natural candidate (contiguous arc = max |μ_1|)
     - But there might be other S with |Stab| = 1 and even higher H

  This gives a CLEAN GROUP-THEORETIC PROOF of the phase transition:
  High symmetry (Paley) wins at degree-2, but rigidity kills at degree-4+.
  Low symmetry (Interval) has the Walsh freedom to optimize higher-degree terms.


